				<wikidot:authorName>ScipperSkipper</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>2739935</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>Headcanon: Canine-reactor and other related technologies are product of the <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/scp-1000">Children of the Night</a>, Dr. Dementyev and SCP-4062 clearly came from the same reality as <a href="http://www.scpwiki.com/scp-2273">SCP-2273</a>.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10458480#post-4458963</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10458480/scp-4062#post-4458963</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Wed, 01 Jan 2020 14:26:48 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>EndlessNameless</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3617744</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>This article took me completely off guard! It crosses the audacity line twice, with such a good idea, and a so good execution, that it doesn't surprised me that in all 4 pages of discussion, there isn't a single mention about the concept looking more like a SCP-J than a main article&#8230; first the dog concept, and second that interview, which maybe is the funniest thing that I have read in this website! I want to +1 twice!</p> <p>Also, for me this is very amusing because my research area is in nuclear physics (for fusion), so I imagine what a tokamak proposal would be&#8230; Maybe two cats playing and throwing away super fast balls ?</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
