					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10458480#post-4172238</guid>
				<title>(no title)</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-10458480/scp-4062#post-4172238</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Mon, 04 Mar 2019 01:41:42 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Lesh</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>1432306</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>That's an interesting comparison!</p> <p>For those that haven't heard of it, &quot;Uncleftish Beholding&quot; is an essay explaining atomic theory in an alternate version of English devoid of Greek, Latin, and French influence. It shows a cool version of what scientific writing may look like in this situation and coins a bunch of Germanic-influenced words.</p> <p>For example, &quot;uncleftish&quot; describes something that cannot be cleft (or split), so it replaces &quot;atomic&quot; which comes from Ancient Greek via Latin and French. &quot;Beholding&quot; likewise replaces &quot;theory&quot;.</p> <p>Here's the first line (with &quot;worldken&quot; replacing &quot;physics&quot;):</p> <blockquote> <p>For most of its being, mankind did not know what things are made of, but could only guess. With the growth of worldken, we began to learn, and today we have a beholding of stuff and work that watching bears out, both in the workstead and in daily life.</p> </blockquote> <p>Learn more on <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncleftish_Beholding">wikipedia</a>!</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
